com.stormpath.sdk.application
Class AccountStoreMappings

java.lang.Object
  com.stormpath.sdk.application.AccountStoreMappings

public final class AccountStoreMappings
extends Object

Static utility/helper methods for working with AccountStoreMapping resources. Most methods are factory methods used for forming AccountStoreMapping-specific fluent DSL queries. for example: 

 AccountStoreMappings.criteria()
     .withApplication()
     .offsetBy(50)
     .limitTo(25));
or 
 AccountStoreMappings.where(AccountStoreMappings.listIndex().eq(3))
     .withAccountStore()
or, if using static imports: 
 import static com.stormpath.sdk.account.AccountStoreMappings.*;

 ...
     criteria()
     .withApplication()
     .offsetBy(50)
     .limitTo(25));
or 
 import static com.stormpath.sdk.account.AccountStoreMappings.*;

 ...

 where(listIndex().eq(3))
     .withAccountStore()

criteria

public static AccountStoreMappingCriteria criteria()
Returns a new AccountStoreMappingCriteria instance to use to formulate an Account query.

Note that it is usually more common to use the where method instead of this one as the where method usually lends to better readability. For example: 

 AccountStoreMappings.criteria().add(AccountStoreMappings.listIndex().eq(8))...
versus: 
 AccountStoreMappings.where(AccountStoreMappings.listIndex().eq(8))...
or when using static imports: 
 where(listIndex().eq(8))...
While all three statements are equivalent, the second and third examples are shorter and probably more readable.

Returns:
a new AccountStoreMappingCriteria instance to use to formulate an AccountStoreMapping query.

listIndex

public static EqualsExpressionFactory listIndex()
Creates a new EqualsExpressionFactory instance reflecting the AccountStoreMapping listIndex property, to be used to construct a listIndex Criterion when building an AccountStoreMappingCriteria query. For example: 
 AccountStoreMappings.where(AccountStoreMappings.listIndex().eq(12);
The above example invokes the returned factory's eq() method. This produces a listIndex-specific Criterion which is added to the criteria query (via the where method). For example, the following code is equivalent: 
 AccountStoreMappingCriteria criteria = AccountStoreMappings.criteria();
 EqualsExpressionFactory listIndexExpressionFactory = AccountStoreMappings.listIndex();
 Criterion listIndexEqualsTen = listIndexExpressionFactory.eq(10);
 criteria.add(listIndexEqualsEnabled);
The first code example is clearly more succinct and readable.

Returns:
a new listIndex-specific EqualsExpressionFactory instance, to be used to construct a criterion when building an AccountStoreMappingCriteria query.
